ords, 13 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\n• Maintenance events on 2026-07-06 at 11:32-11:47 (Setup/Changeover, 15 min duration) and 11:33-11:39 (Scheduled Maintenance, 5 min) on Machine Fra-10 precede Color Mismatch spike by ~2 hours; Paint Booth training (13:04-13:14, 10 min) and meetings (13:12-13:20, 8 min) overlap defect window [source: fetch_downtime_events, 189 rows; fetch_historical_patterns, 67 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\n• Operators Melissa Cameron, Kelsey Kaiser, and Jessica Green each logged 2-3 Color Mismatch defects; Deanna Miller (Weekend Night shift) handled high-volume batch orders (5249: 64 units, 5129: 56 units) with 84-93% completion rates and scrap recorded [source: fetch_operator_logs, 184 rows; fetch_work_orders_context, 290 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\n• Material Shortage event on Machine Pai-32 (12:33-12:44, 10 min) during Color Mismatch window; no direct correlation to specific defect but timing suggests potential supply-side process variation [source: fetch_downtime_events, 189 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\nSUPPORTING DATA\n\n| Defect Time | Machine | Operator | Shift | Root Cause | Action | Product | Severity |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 13:35:09 | Pai-32 | Raymond Ford | Morning | Design Issue | Special Inspection | eBike T200 | 3 |\n| 13:33:25 | Pai-31 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | Material Defect | Process Adjusted | eBike T101 | 3 |\n| 13:28:15 | Pai-32 | Harold Foster | Afternoon | Operator Error | Special Inspection | eBike M300 | 3 |\n| 13:27:39 | Pai-31 | Kelsey Kaiser | Afternoon | Operator Error | Reworked | eBike T200 | 3 |\n| 13:14:07 | Pai-32 | Brian Crosby | Morning | Process Variation | Accepted with Deviation | eBike T200 | 2 |\n| 12:46:59 | Pai-32 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | Process Variation | Repaired | eBike T101 | 3 |\n| 12:40:14 | Pai-32 | Deanna Miller | Weekend Night | Design Issue | Adjusted Process Parameters | eBike C150 | 2 |\n| 12:40:04 | Pai-31 | Jessica Green | Afternoon | Process Variation | Reworked | eBike T200 | 3 |\n| 14:01:30 | Pai-32 | Christopher Jimenez | Night | Process Variation | Repaired | eBike T101 | 3 |\n| 19:02:31 | Qua-71 | Sara Osborn | Morning | Material Defect | Adjusted Process Parameters | eBike T200 | 2 |\n\nGAPS / MISSING DATA\n\n• Cannot determine if Color Mismatch spike is anomalous or recurring pattern—only 7-day window provided; historical trend analysis requires longer baseline [source: data limitation]\n• No direct correlation data between specific maintenance activities and defect occurrence; causality cannot be established from timing alone [source: data limitation]\n• Operator skill/training levels not available; cannot assess whether Operator Error root cause reflects capability gaps or situational factors [source: data limitation]\n• Paint Booth material batch traceability not captured; Material Defect root cause cannot be linked to specific supplier lots or batch dates [source: data limitation]\n\nHANDOFF NOTES\n\n• Escalate Paint and Finish workcenters (Pai-31, Pai-32) for process parameter audit, especially around 13:00-14:00 window; focus on calibration drift post-maintenance (11:32-11:47 changeover) [source: fetch_defect_records, fetch_downtime_events]\n• Review Afternoon shift operator performance (Melissa Cameron, Kelsey Kaiser, Harold Foster) for training gaps; 6 of 13 defects occurred Afternoon shift with Operator Error cited 2x [source: fetch_operator_logs, fetch_defect_records]\n• Investigate Material Shortage event (12:33-12:44 on Pai-32) correlation to Material Defect root causes; cross-reference with paint supply inventory logs for batch quality issues [source: fetch_downtime_events]\n', 'type': 'text'}], 'is_error': False, 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_01NKop6oddto4PdSGLfCM7KC', 'type': 'tool_result'}], 'role': 'user'}, {'content': [{'text': 'Now let me call the Analyzer Agent to perform root cause analysis using the monitoring data:', 'type': 'text'}, {'id': 'toolu_01JbBZPArcJGX9cBWcjExY7S', 'input': {'prompt': 'Perform root cause analysis for Color Mismatch defects over the last 7 days. Analysis scope: OEE Analysis disabled, Downtime Analysis disabled, Changeover Analysis disabled, Maintenance Correlation enabled. Use the following monitoring data: 13 Color Mismatch defects concentrated on 2026-07-06, primarily on Paint and Finish machines Pai-31 and Pai-32 during afternoon shift (13:00-14:00 window). Maintenance events on 2026-07-06 at 11:32-11:47 (Setup/Changeover) and 11:33-11:39 (Scheduled Maintenance) on Machine Fra-10 precede defect spike by ~2 hours. Material Shortage event on Pai-32 at 12:33-12:44. Root causes identified: Machine Calibration, Process Variation, Material Defect, Operator Error, Design Issue. Operators involved: Melissa Cameron, Kelsey Kaiser, Jessica Green, Deanna Miller. Focus analysis on maintenance correlation with defect occurrence and provide statistical confidence ratings for enabled areas.'}, 'name': 'call_analyzer_agent', 'type': 'tool_use'}], 'role': 'assistant'}, {'content': [{'content': [{'text': 'KEY FINDINGS\n\n1. Color Mismatch defects concentrated on Paint/Finish machines Pai-31 and Pai-32 during afternoon shift with 6 documented instances (Severity 1-3), primarily attributed to Process Variation (3 cases), Operator Error (2 cases), and Material Defect (1 case). [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows, 7-day period]\n\n2. Maintenance correlation with defect spike: Scheduled Maintenance on Fra-10 (11:33-11:39, 6 minutes) and Setup/Changeover (11:32-11:47, 15 minutes) precede Color Mismatch spike by ~2 hours; Material Shortage on Pai-32 (12:33-12:44, 11 minutes) occurs 20-30 minutes before peak defect window (13:00-14:00). [source: analyze_downtime_correlations, 181 rows, 7-day period]\n\n3. Operator involvement: Melissa Cameron (2 Color Mismatch defects on Pai-31/Pai-32, Afternoon shift) shows elevated defect association; Kelsey Kaiser and Jessica Green each have 1 Color Mismatch defect during afternoon shifts on Paint machines. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows]\n\n4. Process Variation is the dominant root cause (3 of 6 Color Mismatch defects), suggesting systematic calibration drift or paint application parameter instability rather than isolated operator error. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows]\n\n5. Maintenance-to-defect temporal gap (~2 hours) indicates indirect causation: upstream maintenance on Fra-10 may have disrupted material flow, triggering shortage on Pai-32, which then cascaded into process instability on Pai-31/Pai-32 during afternoon shift. [source: analyze_downtime_correlations, 181 rows]\n\nSUPPORTING DATA\n\n| Defect Type | Machine | Operator | Shift | Root Cause | Severity | Count |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-31 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | Material Defect | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-31 | Kelsey Kaiser | Afternoon | Operator Error | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-31 | Jessica Green | Afternoon | Process Variation | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-32 | Harold Foster | Afternoon | Operator Error | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-32 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | Process Variation | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-32 | Christopher Jimenez | Night | Process Variation | 3 | 1 |\n\nGAPS / MISSING DATA\n\n- Exact timestamps for Color Mismatch defect occurrences not available; analysis relies on shift-level aggregation (Afternoon = 13:00-21:00 window). Cannot pinpoint whether all 13 defects clustered in 13:00-14:00 window or distributed across afternoon shift.\n- Paint application parameters (spray pressure, viscosity, temperature) not captured in defect data; cannot validate whether maintenance on Fra-10 directly caused calibration drift on Pai-31/Pai-32.\n- Material Shortage event on Pai-32 (12:33-12:44) duration is 11 minutes, but defect spike window is 13:00-14:00; recovery time and material queue status unknown.\n- No data on paint batch lot numbers or supplier changes correlating with 2026-07-06 spike; Material Defect root cause cannot be traced to specific material batch.\n\nHANDOFF NOTES\n\n- Prioritize machine calibration audit on Pai-31 and Pai-32: Process Variation dominates (50% of Color Mismatch cases), indicating systematic drift rather than random operator error. Recommend spray pressure and nozzle alignment verification.\n- Investigate material shortage cascade: Material Shortage on Pai-32 (12:33-12:44) preceded defect spike by 20-30 minutes. Verify whether paint supply interruption caused residual viscosity/temperature instability post-recovery.\n- Operator retraining focus: Melissa Cameron (2 defects) and Kelsey Kaiser (1 defect) require process parameter validation training; however, Process Variation dominance suggests equipment-level root cause is primary.\n', 'type': 'text'}], 'is_error': False, 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_01JbBZPArcJGX9cBWcjExY7S', 'type': 'tool_result'}], 'role': 'user'}], 'model': 'claude-haiku-4-5-20251001', 'tools': [{'name': 'call_monitor_agent', 'description': 'Call the Monitor Agent to capture operational data', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_analyzer_agent', 'description': 'Call the Analyzer Agent to perform root cause analysis', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_planner_agent', 'description': 'Call the Planner Agent to create action plans', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_verifier_agent', 'description': 'Call the Verifier Agent to validate findings', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_executor_agent', 'description': '"Call the Executor Agent to execute plans and send notifications', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}], 'system': 'You are the Supervisor Agent for the Manufacturing Execution System (MES) AI workflow.\n\nYour primary responsibility is to orchestrate the complete defect analysis workflow by coordinating five specialized agents:\n\n1. **Monitor Agent**: Captures operational data and contextualizes manufacturing events\n2. **Analyzer Agent**: Performs root cause analysis and identifies correlations\n3. **Planner Agent**: Creates actionable improvement plans and generates reports and return PDF File Name\n4. **Verifier Agent**: Validates findings and manages human validation\n5. **Executor Agent**: Executes action plans and sends email notifications\n\n**Workflow Process:**\n1. Receive defect analysis request with defect type, time period, and analysis scope parameters\n2. Call Monitor Agent to capture comprehensive operational data based on enabled scope\n3. Call Analyzer Agent to perform root cause analysis using monitoring data and scope\n4. Call Planner Agent to create action plans based on analysis results and scope\n5. Call Verifier Agent to validate findings within scope\n6. Call Executor Agent to pass PDF file Name, execute immediate actions and send email notifications with PDF link in format(https://dfmw0zqekwl4n.cloudfront.net/proxy/8501/pdf=pdf_filename.pdf?pdf=pdf_filename.pdf)\n7. Compile complete analysis results with all agent outputs\n\n**Analysis Scope Parameters:**\n- include_oee: Enable/disable OEE performance analysis\n- include_downtime: Enable/disable downtime and stoppages analysis\n- include_changeover: Enable/disable batch changeover analysis\n- include_maintenance: Enable/disable maintenance correlation analysis\n\n**Key Responsibilities:**\n- Ensure proper data flow between agents with scope considerations\n- Maintain analysis context throughout the workflow\n- Coordinate timing and sequencing of agent activities\n- Compile comprehensive results from all agents\n- Handle error recovery and workflow continuity\n- Provide executive summary of complete analysis\n- Respect analysis scope limitations and focus areas\n- Use Executor Agent for one email notification and action execution\n- Pass PDF filename from Planner Agent to Executor Agent for email notifications\n\n**Critical Workflow Note:**\nWhen calling the Planner Agent, extract the PDF filename from the response and pass it to the Executor Agent when calling for email notifications. This ensures the PDF link is included in the email body.\n\n**Output Format:**\nAlways return a structured analysis result containing:\n- Defect type and analysis parameters including scope settings\n- Monitoring results with operational context within enabled scope\n- Root cause analysis with HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW certainty ratings for enabled areas\n- Action plans with timelines and resources for enabled scope\n- Verification results with validation status\n- Execution results with notification status\n- Executive summary with key findings and recommendations\n\nFocus on ensuring each agent receives appropriate context and scope parameters, and that the complete workflow produces actionable, validated insights for manufacturing quality improvement within the specified analysis scope. All email notifications should be handled through the Executor Agent with proper PDF filename passing.\n\n=== OUTPUT RULES (mandatory) ===\n- No emoji, no ASCII-art charts, no decorative separators.\n- Report only numbers that appear in tool results or subagent reports.\n  Never compute totals, percentages, correlations, confidence\n  percentages, or dollar amounts yourself. If a number was not\n  returned by a tool, write "not available in data" instead.\n- Never compare values against industry standards, benchmarks,\n  "world-class" figures, or "required" durations unless those values\n  appear in tool results.\n- Express certainty only as HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW with a one-line reason.\n', 'temperature': 0.2}>
