ce: analyze_downtime_correlations, 181 rows, 7-day period]\n\n3. Operator involvement: Melissa Cameron (2 Color Mismatch defects on Pai-31/Pai-32, Afternoon shift) shows elevated defect association; Kelsey Kaiser and Jessica Green each have 1 Color Mismatch defect during afternoon shifts on Paint machines. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows]\n\n4. Process Variation is the dominant root cause (3 of 6 Color Mismatch defects), suggesting systematic calibration drift or paint application parameter instability rather than isolated operator error. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows]\n\n5. Maintenance-to-defect temporal gap (~2 hours) indicates indirect causation: upstream maintenance on Fra-10 may have disrupted material flow, triggering shortage on Pai-32, which then cascaded into process instability on Pai-31/Pai-32 during afternoon shift. [source: analyze_downtime_correlations, 181 rows]\n\nSUPPORTING DATA\n\n| Defect Type | Machine | Operator | Shift | Root Cause | Severity | Count |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-31 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | Material Defect | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-31 | Kelsey Kaiser | Afternoon | Operator Error | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-31 | Jessica Green | Afternoon | Process Variation | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-32 | Harold Foster | Afternoon | Operator Error | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-32 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | Process Variation | 3 | 1 |\n| Color Mismatch | Pai-32 | Christopher Jimenez | Night | Process Variation | 3 | 1 |\n\nGAPS / MISSING DATA\n\n- Exact timestamps for Color Mismatch defect occurrences not available; analysis relies on shift-level aggregation (Afternoon = 13:00-21:00 window). Cannot pinpoint whether all 13 defects clustered in 13:00-14:00 window or distributed across afternoon shift.\n- Paint application parameters (spray pressure, viscosity, temperature) not captured in defect data; cannot validate whether maintenance on Fra-10 directly caused calibration drift on Pai-31/Pai-32.\n- Material Shortage event on Pai-32 (12:33-12:44) duration is 11 minutes, but defect spike window is 13:00-14:00; recovery time and material queue status unknown.\n- No data on paint batch lot numbers or supplier changes correlating with 2026-07-06 spike; Material Defect root cause cannot be traced to specific material batch.\n\nHANDOFF NOTES\n\n- Prioritize machine calibration audit on Pai-31 and Pai-32: Process Variation dominates (50% of Color Mismatch cases), indicating systematic drift rather than random operator error. Recommend spray pressure and nozzle alignment verification.\n- Investigate material shortage cascade: Material Shortage on Pai-32 (12:33-12:44) preceded defect spike by 20-30 minutes. Verify whether paint supply interruption caused residual viscosity/temperature instability post-recovery.\n- Operator retraining focus: Melissa Cameron (2 defects) and Kelsey Kaiser (1 defect) require process parameter validation training; however, Process Variation dominance suggests equipment-level root cause is primary.\n', 'type': 'text'}], 'is_error': False, 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_01JbBZPArcJGX9cBWcjExY7S', 'type': 'tool_result'}], 'role': 'user'}], 'model': 'claude-haiku-4-5-20251001', 'system': 'You are the Supervisor Agent for the Manufacturing Execution System (MES) AI workflow.\n\nYour primary responsibility is to orchestrate the complete defect analysis workflow by coordinating five specialized agents:\n\n1. **Monitor Agent**: Captures operational data and contextualizes manufacturing events\n2. **Analyzer Agent**: Performs root cause analysis and identifies correlations\n3. **Planner Agent**: Creates actionable improvement plans and generates reports and return PDF File Name\n4. **Verifier Agent**: Validates findings and manages human validation\n5. **Executor Agent**: Executes action plans and sends email notifications\n\n**Workflow Process:**\n1. Receive defect analysis request with defect type, time period, and an